[{"location":"lib/polarization/#Polarization","page":"Polarization","title":"Polarization","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/polarization/","page":"Polarization","title":"Polarization","text":"Modules = [ElectronGas.Polarization]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/polarization/#ElectronGas.Polarization.Polarization0_FiniteTemp","page":"Polarization","title":"ElectronGas.Polarization.Polarization0_FiniteTemp","text":"function Polarization0_FiniteTemp(q, n, param, maxk=20, scaleN=20, minterval=1e-6, gaussN=10)\n\nFinite temperature one-spin Π0 function for matsubara frequency and momentum. Analytically sum over transfer frequency and angular dependence of momentum, and numerically calculate integration of magnitude of momentum. Slower(~200μs) than Polarization0ZeroTemp. Assume G0^{-1} = iω_n - (k^2/(2m) - mu)\n\n#Arguments:\n\nq: momentum\nn: matsubara frequency given in integer s.t. ωn=2πTn\nparam: other system parameters\nmaxk: optional, upper limit of integral -> maxk*kF\nscaleN: optional, N of Log grid in LogDensedGrid, check CompositeGrids for more detail\nminterval: optional, actual minterval of grid is this value times min(q,kF)\ngaussN: optional, N of GaussLegendre grid in LogDensedGrid.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"lib/polarization/#ElectronGas.Polarization.Polarization0_ZeroTemp-Tuple{Float64, Int64, Any}","page":"Polarization","title":"ElectronGas.Polarization.Polarization0_ZeroTemp","text":"function Polarization0_ZeroTemp(q, n, param)\n\nZero temperature one-spin Π0 function for matsubara frequency and momentum. For low temperature the finite temperature polarization could be approximated with this function to run faster(~200ns). Assume G0^{-1} = iωn - (k^2/(2m) - E_F).\n\n#Arguments:\n\nq: momentum\nn: matsubara frequency given in integer s.t. ωn=2πTn\nparam: other system parameters\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/polarization/#ElectronGas.Polarization.Polarization0wrapped-Union{Tuple{SGT}, Tuple{Any, Any, SGT, Any}, Tuple{Any, Any, SGT, Any, Any}} where SGT","page":"Polarization","title":"ElectronGas.Polarization.Polarization0wrapped","text":"function Polarization0wrapped(Euv, rtol, sgrid::SGT, param, polatype=:zerotemp) where{TGT, SGT}\n\nΠ0 function for matsubara frequency and momentum. Use Polarization0ZeroTemp by default, Polarization0FiniteTemp when pifunc is specified. Assume G0^{-1} = iωn - (k^2/(2m) - E_F). Return full polarization0 function stored in GreenFunc.GreenBasic.Green2DLR.\n\n#Arguments:\n\nEuv: Euv of DLRGrid\nrtol: rtol of DLRGrid\nsgrid: momentum grid\nparam: other system parameters\npifunc: single point Π0 function used. Require form with pifunc(k, n, param).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/twopoint/#Two-point-correlators","page":"Two-point correlators","title":"Two-point correlators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/twopoint/","page":"Two-point correlators","title":"Two-point correlators","text":"Modules = [ElectronGas.TwoPoint]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/twopoint/#ElectronGas.TwoPoint","page":"Two-point correlators","title":"ElectronGas.TwoPoint","text":"Provide N-body response and correlation functions\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"lib/twopoint/#ElectronGas.TwoPoint.LindhardΩnFiniteTemperature-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Int64, T, Int64, T, T, T, T, Any}} where T<:AbstractFloat","page":"Two-point correlators","title":"ElectronGas.TwoPoint.LindhardΩnFiniteTemperature","text":"LindhardΩnFiniteTemperature(dim::Int, q::T, n::Int, μ::T, kF::T, β::T, m::T, spin) where {T <: AbstractFloat}\n\nCompute the polarization function of free electrons at a given frequency. Relative Accuracy is about ~ 1e-6\n\nArguments\n\ndim: dimension\nq: external momentum, q<1e-4 will be treated as q=0 \nn: externel Matsubara frequency, ωn=2π*n/β\nμ: chemical potential\nkF: Fermi momentum \nβ: inverse temperature\nm: mass\nspin : number of spins\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/twopoint/#ElectronGas.TwoPoint.dWRPA-NTuple{9, Any}","page":"Two-point correlators","title":"ElectronGas.TwoPoint.dWRPA","text":"3D Imaginary-time effective interaction derived from random phase approximation.  Return dW_0(q τ)v_q where v_q is the bare Coulomb interaction and dW_0 is the dynamic part of the effective interaction. \n\nThe total effective interaction can be recoverd using,  \n\nW_0(q τ) = v_q δ(τ) + dW_0(q τ)\n\nThe dynamic contribution is the fourier transform of,\n\ndW_0(q iω_n)=v_q^2 Π(q iω_n)(1-v_q Π(q iω_n))\n\nNote that this dynamic contribution dW_0 diverges at small q For this reason this function returnsdW0/vq``\n\nArguments\n\nvqinv: inverse bare interaction as a function of q\nqgrid: one-dimensional array of the external momentum q\nτgrid: one-dimensional array of the imaginary-time\ndim: dimension\nμ: chemical potential\nkF: Fermi momentum \nβ: inverse temperature\nspin : number of spins\nmass: mass\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/twopoint/#ElectronGas.TwoPoint.freePropagatorT-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"Two-point correlators","title":"ElectronGas.TwoPoint.freePropagatorT","text":"freePropagatorT(type, τ, ω, β)\n\nImaginary-time propagator.\n\nArguments\n\ntype: symbol :fermi, :bose\nτ: the imaginary time, must be (-β, β]\nω: dispersion ϵ_k-μ\nβ = 1.0: the inverse temperature \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/twopoint/#ElectronGas.TwoPoint.freePropagatorΩ-Tuple{Any, Int64, Any, Any}","page":"Two-point correlators","title":"ElectronGas.TwoPoint.freePropagatorΩ","text":"freePropagatorΩ(type, n, ω, β=1.0)\n\nMatsubara-frequency kernel of different type\n\nArguments\n\ntype: symbol :fermi, :bose, :corr\nn: index of the Matsubara frequency\nω: dispersion ϵ_k-μ\nβ: the inverse temperature \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"manual/polarization/#Polarization-of-free-electron","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/polarization/#Generic-formalism","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Generic formalism","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"The bare polarization is defined as","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"beginaligned\nPi_0(Omega_n vecq)=\n-S Tsum_mintfracd^d k(2pi)^dG_0(omega_m veck)G_0(omega_m+Omega_n veck+vecq)\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"in the matsubara representation, where S is spin number, G_0 is bare Green's function. We have","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"beginaligned\nG_0(omega_m veck)=frac1iomega_m-epsilon_veck\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"with bare electron dispersion given by epsilon_veck. By summing over frequency we have ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"beginaligned\nPi_0(Omega_n vecq) = -S intfracd^d vec k(2pi)^d\nfracn(epsilon_veck+vecq)-n(epsilon_veck)iomega_n-epsilon_veck+vecq+epsilon_veck \n=-Sint fracd^d vec k(2pi)^d n(epsilon_vec k) left frac1iOmega+epsilon_vec k-epsilon_vec k+vec q-frac1iOmega+epsilon_vec k-vec q-epsilon_vec kright\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"with the fermi distribution function ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"n(epsilon_vec k) =frac1e^betavarepsilon_veck+1","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/#Free-electron-in-3D","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Free electron in 3D","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"From now on we consider free electron in 3D, where d=3 and dispersion epsilon_veck=k^22m-mu. We have","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"beginaligned\nPi_0(Omega vecq)=-Sint_0^infty frack^2dk4pi^2 n(epsilon_k) int_-1^1 d(cos theta) left frac1iOmega+epsilon_vec k-epsilon_vec k+vec q-frac1iOmega+epsilon_vec k-vec q-epsilon_vec kright\n=-Sint_0^infty frack^2dk4pi^2 n(epsilon_k) fracmkqlnfrac4m^2Omega^2+(q^2-2kq)^24m^2Omega^2+(q^2+2kq)^2 \nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"which could be handled with one dimensional integral of k.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization/","page":"Polarization of free electron","title":"Polarization of free electron","text":"In the limit q^2+2k_F q ll 2mOmega_n, the intergrand of Pi_0 is expanded as \nfracmkqlnfrac4m^2Omega^2+(q^2-2kq)^24m^2Omega^2+(q^2+2kq)^2=-frac2q^2mOmega^2+frac2k^2q^4m^3Omega^4+frac(-4k^2+m^2Omega^2)q^62m^5Omega^6+\nZero temperature polarization can be calculated explicitly\nPi_0(Omegaq) = -fracN_F2left1-frac18 k_F qleft leftfrac(i2mOmega-q^2)^2q^2-4 k_F^2rightlogleft(fraci2mOmega-q^2-2 k_F qi2mOmega-q^2+2 k_F qright)+leftfrac(i2mOmega+q^2)^2q^2-4 k_F^2rightlogleft(fraci2mOmega+q^2+2 k_F qi2mOmega+q^2-2 k_F qright)rightright\nIn the static limit Omega=0, \nPi_0(0 q) = -N_F F(q2k_F) \nwhere N_F=Smk_F(2pi^2) is the density of states, and F(x)=frac12-fracx^2-14xln leftfrac1+x1-xright is the Lindhard function. \nThe weak logarithmic singularity near 2k_F is the cause of the Friedel oscillation and Kohn-Luttinger superconductivity.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/#Polarization-of-free-electron-in-two-dimensions","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"We consider the polarziation of free electron gas in 2D, ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"Pi_0(q Omega_n)\n=-Sintfracd^2 vec k(2pi)^2\nfracn(epsilon_veck)-n(epsilon_veck+vecq)iOmega_n+epsilon_veck-epsilon_veck+vecq","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"where n(vec k) = 1(e^beta(epsilon_vec k-mu)+1), epsilon_vec k=k^2(2m)-mu, and S is the spin factor. It is expressed as","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"Pi_0(q Omega_n)=-Sint_0^infty fracmkdk2pi^2 n(epsilon_k) int_0^2pi dtheta left frac1i2mOmega_n-2kq costheta-q^2-frac1i2mOmega_n-2kqcos theta+q^2right","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/#Static-limit-\\Omega_n0","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Static limit Omega_n=0","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"For real ab, the integral int_0^2pifrac1a-bcos theta=frac2pisqrta^2-b^2 and int_0^2pifrac1a+bcos theta=Cfrac2pisqrta^2-b^2 where C=1 for ab and C=-1 for ab. Hence, we have \t","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"Pi_0(q 0)= -Sint_0^q2fracmkdk2pi^2 n(epsilon_k) frac4pisqrtq^4-4k^2q^2","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"At zero temperature, ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"for q2k_F, \nPi_0(q 0)=-Sint_0^q2 fracmpi q fracdk^2sqrtq^2-4k^2=-int_0^1fracmS4pifracdxsqrt1-x=-fracmS2pi \nfor  q2k_F, \nPi_0(q 0)=-Sint_0^k_F fracmpi q fracdk^2sqrtq^2-4k^2=-int_0^4k_F^2q^2fracmS4pifracdxsqrt1-x=-fracmS2pileft( 1-sqrt1-frac4k_F^2q^2right) ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/#Zero-temperature","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Zero temperature","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"Pi_0(q Omega_n)=-fracmS2pi left1-frac2k_Fqrm Resqrtleft(fracq2k_F+ i fracmOmega_nqk_Fright)^2-1 right ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/polarization_2D/","page":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","title":"Polarization of free electron in two dimensions","text":"For qto 0 and Omega_n neq 0, Pi_0(q Omega_n) to 0.","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/legendreinteraction/#Legendre-Decomposed-Interaction","page":"Legendre Decomposed Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposed Interaction","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposed Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposed Interaction","text":"Modules = [ElectronGas.LegendreInteraction]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/legendreinteraction/#ElectronGas.LegendreInteraction","page":"Legendre Decomposed Interaction","title":"ElectronGas.LegendreInteraction","text":"Provide Legendre decomposed interaction that could be useful for calculating self-energy and solving gap-function equation of superconductivity problems.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/#Legendre-Decomposition-of-Interaction","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/#Why-decompose?","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Why decompose?","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"In many cases we need to calculate integrals of the following form:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"   beginaligned\nDelta(veck) = int fracd^dp2pi^d W(veck-vecp) F(vecp)\n   endaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"where only momentum dependency is of our concern. In such cases we assume that the interaction depends only on the magnitude of the momentum difference, and the other part of the integrand has some sort of space symmetry.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"Two typical cases are the calculation of self-energy and gap-function equation. In the case of self-energy, the other part of the integrand depends only on the magnitude of the momentum, thus we can integrate out the angular dependence to simplify the calculation. In the case of gap-function equation, we do not know priorly the symmetry of anomalous correlator, but we can always decompose the interaction and anomalous correlator into angular momentum channels. In that sense the self-energy case is actually a special case where we only care about s-channel.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/#How?","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"How?","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"From now on we illustrate 3D case.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"We first express the interaction in Legendre polynomials:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"   beginaligned\nW(veck-vecp)=sum_l=0^inftyfrac2l+12 w_l(k p) p_l(hatkp)\n=2pisum_lm w_l(k p) Y_lm(hatkk)Y_lm^*(hatpp)\n   endaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"with","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"   beginaligned\nw_l(k p) = int_-1^1dchi P_l(chi) W(sqrtk^2+p^2-2kpchi)\n   endaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"The other part of the integrand could also be decomposed as","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"   beginaligned\nf_lm(k) = int dhatkY_lm(hatkk)F(veck)\n   endaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"In the cases mentioned above there's no dependency on m, thus the whole calculation could be decomposed with l.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"For gap-function equation we have","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"   beginaligned\nDelta_l(k) = int fracp^2dp4pi^2 w_l(k p) f_l(p)\n   endaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"and for self-energy we have","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"   beginaligned\nSigma(k) = int fracp^2dp4pi^2 w_0(k p) G(p)\n   endaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/#Helper-function","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Helper function","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"We can do the decomposition with helper function:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"beginaligned\nH_n(y) = int_0^y z^n W(z)dz\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"Then","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"beginaligned\nint_k-p^k+p z^n W(z)dz = H_n(k+p)-H_n(k-p)= delta H_n(k p)\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"Thus all integral for w_l could be expressed as combination of helper functions:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction/","page":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","title":"Legendre Decomposition of Interaction","text":"   beginaligned\nw_0(kp) = frac1kp delta H_1(k p) \nw_1(kp) = frac12(kp)^2 (k^2+p^2)delta H_1(k p)-delta H_3(k p) \nw_2(kp) = frac1(2kp)^3\n3(k^2+p^2)^2-4k^2p^2delta H_1(k p)-6(k^2+p^2)delta H_3(k p)+3delta H_5(k p) \n   endaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/interaction/#Interaction","page":"Interaction","title":"Interaction","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/interaction/","page":"Interaction","title":"Interaction","text":"Modules = [ElectronGas.Interaction]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/interaction/#ElectronGas.Interaction.KO-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"Interaction","title":"ElectronGas.Interaction.KO","text":"function KO(q, n, param)\n\nDynamic part of KO interaction, with polarization approximated by zero temperature Π0. Returns the spin symmetric part and asymmetric part separately.\n\n#Arguments:\n\nq: momentum\nn: matsubara frequency given in integer s.t. ωn=2πTn\nparam: other system parameters\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/interaction/#ElectronGas.Interaction.RPA-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"Interaction","title":"ElectronGas.Interaction.RPA","text":"function RPA(q, n, param)\n\nDynamic part of RPA interaction, with polarization approximated by zero temperature Π0.\n\n#Arguments:\n\nq: momentum\nn: matsubara frequency given in integer s.t. ωn=2πTn\nparam: other system parameters\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/interaction/#ElectronGas.Interaction.coulomb-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Interaction","title":"ElectronGas.Interaction.coulomb","text":"function coulomb(q,param)\n\nBare interaction in momentum space. Coulomb interaction if Λs=0, Yukawa otherwise.\n\n#Arguments:\n\nq: momentum\nparam: other system parameters\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/interaction/#ElectronGas.Interaction.landauParameterTakada-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"Interaction","title":"ElectronGas.Interaction.landauParameterTakada","text":"TODO    function landauParameterTakada(q, n, param)->exchange correlation kernel/Landau parameter\n\nG factor with Takada's anzats. See Takada(doi:10.1103/PhysRevB.47.5202)(Eq.2.13-2.16). Now Landau parameter F. F(+-)=G(+-)*V\n\n#Arguments:\n\nq: momentum\nn: matsubara frequency given in integer s.t. ωn=2πTn\nparam: other system parameters\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/convention/#Convention","page":"Convention","title":"Convention","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/convention/","page":"Convention","title":"Convention","text":"Modules = [ElectronGas.Convention]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/convention/#ElectronGas.Convention","page":"Convention","title":"ElectronGas.Convention","text":"Template of convention.\n\nStores conventions that will not change for all purposes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/#Decomposition-of-Interaction-in-two-dimensions","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"In GW-approximation, we calculation self-energy as","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"Sigma(mathbfkomega_n)=-Tint fracrm d^d mathbfq(2pi)^d sum_m G(mathbfpomega_m)W(mathbfk-pomega_n-omega_m) \ntag1 ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"where G is the Green's function and W is the effective interaction. Here, we suppress spin index.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/#Spherical-harmonic-representation","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Spherical harmonic representation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"We first express the W(qtau) function as an expansion in Legendre polynomials P_ell(chi)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"begingathered\nW(mathbfk-mathbfp tau)=sum_ell=0^infty barw_ell(k p tau) P_ell(hatk p)  \nbarw_ell(k p tau)=fracN(dell)2 int_-1^1 d chi P_ell(chi) Wleft(sqrtk^2+p^2-2 k p chi tauright)\nendgathered","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"Since the Legendre polynomials of a scalar product of unit vectors can be expanded with spherical harmonics using","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"P_ell(hatk p)=fracOmega_dN(dell) sum_m=1^N(dell) Y_ell m(hatk) Y_ell m^*(hatp)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"where Omega_d is the solid angle in d dimensions, and ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"N(d ell)=frac2 ell+d-2ellleft(\nbeginarrayc\nell+d-3 \nell-1\nendarrayright)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"denotes the number of linearly independent homogeneous harmonic polynomials of degree ell in d dimensions. The spherical harmonics are orthonormal as ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"int rm dOmega_hat k Y_ell m(hat k)  Y_ell^prime m^prime(hat k)  = delta_ell ell^prime delta_mm^prime ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"Hence, the W(qtau) function can expressed further on as","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"W(mathbfk-mathbfp tau)=sum_ell fracOmega_dN(dell)  barw_ell(k p tau) sum_m Y_ell m(hatk) Y_ell m^*(hatp)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"or ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"W(mathbfk-mathbfp tau)= fracOmega_d2sum_ell  w_ell(k p tau) sum_m Y_ell m(hatk) Y_ell m^*(hatp )","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"with ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"w_ell(k p tau)=int_-1^1 d chi P_ell(chi) Wleft(sqrtk^2+p^2-2 k p chi tauright)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"In addition, the Green's function G(mathbf p tau) has ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"beginaligned\n\tG(mathbf p tau)= sum_ell=0^inftysum_m=1^N(dell) G_ell m(ptau) Y_ell m(hat p) \n\tG_ell m(ptau) = int rm dOmega_hat k G(mathbf ptau) Y^*_ell m(hat p)\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/#Decouple-with-channels","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decouple with channels","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"By the sphereical harmonic expansion of Eq.(1), the self-energy ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"beginaligned\nsum_ell m Sigma_ell m (ktau)Y_ell m(hat k) = fracOmega_d2 int fracrm dmathbf p(2pi)^d sum_ell mG_ell m(p tau) Y_ell m(hat p) sum_ell^prime m^prime w_ell^prime(kptau)   Y_ell^prime m^prime(hatk) Y_ell^prime m^prime^*(hatp ) \n=fracOmega_d2 sum_ell m int fracp^d-1dp(2pi)^d G_ell m(p tau) w_ell(kptau) Y_ell m(hat k)\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"Since self-energy is symmertric with hat k, we just need to project on the s-wave channel, namely","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"Sigma(ktau) =fracOmega_d2  int fracp^d-1dp(2pi)^d G(ptau) w_0(kptau)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/#Two-dimensions","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Two dimensions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"beginaligned\nN(2ell) = 2 \nY_ell 1(hat k) = cos(ell theta)  Y_ell 2(hat k) = sin(ell theta) \nP_ell(hatkp) =  pi cosell(theta_hat k - theta_hat p)\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"Hence, the self-energy is ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/legendreinteraction_2D/","page":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","title":"Decomposition of Interaction in two dimensions","text":"Sigma(ktau) = int fracpdp4pi G(ptau)w_0(kptau)","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/selfenergy/#Self-Energy","page":"Self Energy","title":"Self Energy","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/selfenergy/","page":"Self Energy","title":"Self Energy","text":"Modules = [ElectronGas.SelfEnergy]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/parameter/#Parameter","page":"Parameter","title":"Parameter","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/parameter/","page":"Parameter","title":"Parameter","text":"Modules = [ElectronGas.Parameter]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/parameter/#ElectronGas.Parameter","page":"Parameter","title":"ElectronGas.Parameter","text":"Template of parameter. A submodule of ElectronGas.\n\nUse the convention where ħ=1, k_B=1.\nOnly stores parameters that might change for purposes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"lib/parameter/#ElectronGas.Parameter.defaultUnit","page":"Parameter","title":"ElectronGas.Parameter.defaultUnit","text":"function defaultUnit(Θ, rs)\n\nassume 4πϵ0=1, me=0.5, EF=1\n\n#Arguments:\n\nΘ: dimensionless temperature. Since EF=1 we have β=beta\nrs: Wigner-Seitz radius over Bohr radius.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"lib/parameter/#ElectronGas.Parameter.fullUnit","page":"Parameter","title":"ElectronGas.Parameter.fullUnit","text":"function fullUnit(ϵ0, e0, me, EF, β)\n\ngenerate Para with a complete set of parameters, no value presumed.\n\n#Arguments:\n\nϵ0: vacuum permittivity\ne0: electron charge\nme: electron mass\nEF: Fermi energy\nβ: inverse temperature\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"lib/parameter/#ElectronGas.Parameter.rydbergUnit","page":"Parameter","title":"ElectronGas.Parameter.rydbergUnit","text":"function rydbergUnit(Θ, rs)\n\nassume 4πϵ0=1, me=0.5, e0=sqrt(2)\n\n#Arguments:\n\nΘ: dimensionless temperature. beta could be different from β\nrs: Wigner-Seitz radius over Bohr radius.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = ElectronGas","category":"page"},{"location":"#ElectronGas","page":"Home","title":"ElectronGas","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for ElectronGas.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"#Library-Outline","page":"Home","title":"Library Outline","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Pages = [\n    \"lib/twopoint.md\",\n]\nDepth = 1","category":"page"}]
